Anon, I'm with
>>39308057
It's not as out of place anymore as you think. Remember, nobody bat's an eye at cartoons and films with anthropomorphic characters - it's the sheer volume of NSFW shit shedding light on the furry fandom that is shocking. But that doesn't dour the content of the original work in any way. You're not the only author to fear this - you're also not the only author who has fallen into the trap of going with or without. Authors who retain their anthro characters do just fine. The value is in the distinctions it creates between civilizations. If you skin-swap your anthros with humans, you risk feeling like you're writing just another For Honor fantasy with Mayans fighting Persians—your readers will note that, too. It gets boring, and your readers can FEEL when you're pulling your punches.
A lot more sci-fi is getting published with those lines crossed and enjoying no less success than their human-bleached counterparts, and I guarantee even MS space operas like Star Trek will follow suit pretty soon. People want more exotic elements in their fantasy - eggplant & parsley-themed humans aren't all that's on the table anymore, and your modern reader has broader expectations than we did when we were younger, and even WE were disappointed by the dearth of more exotic species in our fantasy.
Lemme close with saying that I'm with you 100% no matter what direction you take; this is your work, and more than anything, you deserve to feel every ounce of pride and accomplishment (and praise!) you'll receive when you publish it, no matter where that is. Trust yourself, not your fear. If you DO opt to skin-swap your characters and species, then just be sure you feel just in doing so—don't leave yourself exposed to any potential for regret. You deserve better than that, and don't ever forget it.
